| url-status = live
}}</ref>

Herzog publicly admitted the need for some change in the NLRA, but privately he opposed the proposed Taft–Hartley amendments. He felt the communist oath provisions were unconstitutional, that the amendments would turn the NLRA into a management weapon, that creation of an independent General Counsel would weaken the NLRB, and that the law's dismantling of the agency's economic analysis unit deprived the NLRB of essential expertise.{{sfn|Gross|2010|pp=11–13}} Nonetheless, Congress overrode Truman's veto of the Taft–Hartley Act on June 23, 1947, and the bill became law.{{sfn|Lee|1980|pp=101–03}}

The Taft–Hartley Act fundamentally changed the nature of federal labor law, but it also seriously hindered the NLRB's ability to enforce the law. The loss of the mediation function left the NLRB unable to become involved in labor disputes, a function it had engaged in since its inception as the National Labor Board in 1933. This hindered the agency's efforts to study, analyze, and create bulwarks against [[Good faith|bad-faith]] [[collective bargaining]]; reduced its ability to formulate national labor policy in this area; and left the agency making labor law on an ineffective, time-consuming case-by-case basis.{{sfn|Lambert|2005|p=104}} The separation of the General Counsel from supervision by the national board also had significant impact on the agency. This separation was enacted against the advice of the Justice Department, contradicted the policy Congress had enacted in the Administrative Procedure Act of 1946, and ignored Millis' extensive internal reforms. The change left the NLRB as the only federal agency unable to coordinate its decision-making and legal activities, and the only agency exempted in this manner under the Administrative Procedure Act. The separation of the General Counsel was not discussed by the committee or by any witnesses during the legislation's mark-up. Indeed, there was no basis for it at all in the public record.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=264}} It was, in the words of sociologist Robin Stryker, "little-noted" and "unprecedented".{{sfn|Stryker|1989|p=344}}

The anti-communist oath provisions generated extensive public debate, and generated disputes before the Supreme Court several times. The Taft–Hartley oath first reached the court in ''[[American Communications Ass'n v. Douds]]'', {{Ussc|339|382|1950|el=no}}, in which the court held 5-to-1 that the oath did not violate the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]], was not an ''[[ex post facto]]'' law or [[bill of attainder]] in violation of [[Article One of the United States Constitution#Section 10: Limits on the States|Article One, Section 10]], and was not a "test oath" in violation of [[Article Six of the United States Constitution#Oaths|Article Six]]. The issue again came before the court in ''[[Garner v. Board of Public Works]]'', {{Ussc|341|716|1951|el=no}}, in which the court unanimously held that a municipal [[loyalty oath]] was not an ''ex post facto law'' or bill of attainder. It came before the court yet a third time in ''Wieman v. Updegraff'', {{Ussc|344|183|1952|el=no}}. This time, the outcome was radically different. The Supreme Court unanimously ruled that state loyalty oath legislation violated the [[due process]] clause of the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]]. In 1965, the Supreme Court held 5-to-4 that the anti-communist oath was a bill of attainder in ''[[United States v. Brown (1965)|United States v. Brown]]'', {{Ussc|381|437|1965|el=no}}.<ref>"Beyond Process: A Substantive Rationale for the Bill of Attainder Clause." ''Virginia Law Review''. April 1984, p. 485.</ref> The Supreme Court essentially overturned ''Douds'', but did not formally do so.{{sfn|Rabinowitz|1996|p=56}}

===1966–2007: Expansion of jurisdiction===
In 1974, Congress amended the National Labor Relations Act to protect employees of non-profit hospitals and allow the Board to adjudicate their claims. The 1935 Wagner Act had protected non-profit hospital workers, but the Taft–Hartley Act removed those protections in 1947. Congress had expressed concern about the impact of potential labor strikes on patient care, but decided that the proposed legislation was an appropriate compromise.<ref name="auto">{{Cite web|title=1974 Health Care Amendments |publisher=National Labor Relations Board|url=https://www.nlrb.gov/about-nlrb/who-we-are/our-history/1974-health-care-amendments|access-date=2021-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Board|first=United States National Labor Relations|date=1986|title=NLRB, the first 50 years: the story of the National Labor Relations Board, 1935-1985.|url=https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc6386/m1/2/|access-date=2021-02-11|publisher=UNT Digital Library|language=English}}</ref>

In July 1987, the Board began work on a comprehensive regulation for collective-bargaining units in health care organizations. The Board held 14 days of hearings and considered testimony from 144 witnesses and over 1,800 public comments, and finally issued the rule in April 1989. The rule was challenged in court and ultimately reached the Supreme Court, which unanimously upheld the rule in April 1991.<ref name="auto"/>

===2007–2014: Lack of quorum and legal challenges===
From December 2007 to mid-July 2013, the agency never had all five members, and not once did it operate with three confirmed members, creating a legal controversy.<ref>Landler, Mark and Greenhouse, Steven. [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/16/us/politics/vacancies-and-partisan-fighting-put-labor-relations-agency-in-legal-limbo.html "Vacancies and Partisan Fighting Put Labor Relations Agency in Legal Limbo"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170521072717/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/16/us/politics/vacancies-and-partisan-fighting-put-labor-relations-agency-in-legal-limbo.html|date=2017-05-21}}, ''New York Times'', July 15, 2013; accessed July 16, 2013.</ref> Three members' terms expired in December 2007, leaving the NLRB with just two members—Chairman [[Wilma B. Liebman]] and Member Peter Schaumber.<ref name="Hananel">Hananel, Sam. [http://www.boston.com/news/nation/washington/articles/2009/09/07/on_labor_day_us_labor_board_remains_in_gridlock "On Labor Day, Labor Board Still in Gridlock"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090911101756/http://www.boston.com/news/nation/washington/articles/2009/09/07/on_labor_day_us_labor_board_remains_in_gridlock/ |date=2009-09-11 }}, ''Boston Globe'', September 7, 2009.</ref> President [[George W. Bush]] refused to make some nominations to the Board and Senate [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] refused to confirm those which he did make.<ref name="Hananel"/><ref name="Hananel2">Hananel, Sam. "Justice Asks High Court to OK Labor Board Rulings", ''Associated Press'', September 29, 2009.</ref><ref name="Greenhouse">[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/15/us/politics/15nlrb.html Greenhouse, Steven. "Labor Panel Is Stalled by Dispute on Nominee"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170318175920/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/15/us/politics/15nlrb.html |date=2017-03-18 }}, ''[[The New York Times]].'' January 14, 2010.</ref>

On December 28, 2007, just before the Board lost its quorum, the four members agreed to delegate their authority to a three-person panel per the [[National Labor Relations Act]].<ref name="Greenhouse"/><ref name="CCHLabor">[http://hr.cch.com/news/employment/011008a.asp "NLRB Temporarily Delegates Litigation Authority to General Counsel"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708125844/http://hr.cch.com/news/employment/011008a.asp |date=2011-07-08 }}, ''CCH/Aspen Labor & Employment Law.'' January 10, 2008.</ref> Only Liebman and Schaumber remained on the Board, but the Board concluded that the two constituted a [[quorum]] of the three-person panel and thus could make decisions on behalf of the Board.<ref name="Greenhouse"/><ref name="CCHLabor"/> Liebman and Schaumber informally agreed to decide only those cases which were in their view noncontroversial and on which they could agree, and issued almost 400 decisions between January 2008 and September 2009.<ref name="Hananel"/><ref name="Hananel2"/><ref name="Greenhouse"/><ref name="InsideCounsel">"Court Invalidates Two-Member NLRB Decision", ''Inside Counsel'', July 2009.</ref>{{full citation needed|date=January 2016}}<ref name="Pickler">Pickler, Nedra. "NLRB Decisions Cause Conflicting Court Opinions." ''Associated Press'', May 1, 2009.</ref>

In April 2009, President Obama nominated Craig Becker (Associate General Counsel of the [[Service Employees International Union]]), [[Mark Gaston Pearce]] (a member on the Industrial Board of Appeals, an agency of the New York State Department of Labor), and Brian Hayes (Republican Labor Policy Director for the [[United States Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions|Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor and Pensions]]) to fill the three empty seats on the NLRB.<ref name="Hananel" />

The U.S. Courts of Appeals for the [[United States Court of Appeals for the First Circuit|First]], [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit|Second]], and [[United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit|Seventh]] Circuits upheld the two-member NLRB's authority to decide cases, while the [[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit|U.S. Court of Appeals for the D.C. Circuit]] rejected its authority.<ref name="Hananel" /><ref name="Hananel2" /><ref name="InsideCounsel" />{{full citation needed|date=January 2016}}<ref name="Pickler" /> In September 2009, the [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] asked the [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]] to immediately hear its appeal from the Seventh Circuit's decision in ''New Process Steel, L.P. v. NLRB'' and settle the dispute, given the high stakes involved.<ref name="Hananel2" /> The Supreme Court granted [[certiorari]] in October and agreed to decide the issue.<ref>"U.S. Supreme Court to Rule on National Labor Relations Board Issue", ''Lawyers USA'', November 2, 2009; [https://www.theguardian.com/world/feedarticle/8786398 "Court to Decide If Two-Person Labor Board Legal"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201206215837/https://www.theguardian.com/info/2015/dec/09/removed-news-agency-feed-article |date=2020-12-06 }}, ''Associated Press.'' November 2, 2009.</ref>

Becker's nomination appeared to fail on February 8, 2010, after Republican Senators (led by [[John McCain]]) threatened to filibuster his nomination.<ref name="Greenhouse" /><ref name="Failed">[http://voices.washingtonpost.com/federal-eye/2010/02/nlrb_nominee_craig_becker_fail.html O'Keefe, Ed. "Craig Becker, nominated for NLRB, rejected by Senate"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921063646/http://voices.washingtonpost.com/federal-eye/2010/02/nlrb_nominee_craig_becker_fail.html|date=2012-09-21}}, ''Washington Post''. February 9, 2010.</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/12/us/politics/12confirm.html "Senate Confirms 2 Dozen Obama Nominees"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180814022928/https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/12/us/politics/12confirm.html|date=2018-08-14}}, ''New York Times.'' February 11, 2010.</ref> President Obama said he would consider making [[recess appointment]]s to the NLRB due to the Senate's failure to move on any of the three nominations.<ref name="Failed" /> On March 27, 2010, Obama recess appointed Becker and Pearce.<ref>{{cite web|author=The White House, Office of the Press Secretary|date=March 27, 2010|title=President Obama Announces Recess Appointments to Key Administration Positions|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/president-obama-announces-recess-appointments-key-administration-positions|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170127013154/https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/president-obama-announces-recess-appointments-key-administration-positions|via=[[NARA|National Archives]]|work=[[whitehouse.gov]]|archive-date=January 27, 2017}}</ref>

On June 17, 2010, the Supreme Court ruled in ''[[New Process Steel, L. P. v. NLRB]]'' that the two-member Board had no authority to issue decisions, invalidating all rulings made by Liebman and Schaumber.<ref>''New Process Steel, L.P. v. NLRB,'' 560 U.S. 674 (2010).</ref>

On June 22, 2010, a [[voice vote]] in the Senate confirmed Pearce to a full term, allowing him to serve until August 27, 2013. The same day, the Senate confirmed Republican nominee Brian Hayes of Massachusetts by voice vote. Effective August 28, 2011, Pearce was named chairman to replace Democrat Wilma Liebman, whose term had expired.<ref>Geman, B.[http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/178489-labor-board-chief-departs-as-uncertainty-for-panel-looms "NLRB chairwoman departs; political fights loom for labor panel"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002235816/http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/178489-labor-board-chief-departs-as-uncertainty-for-panel-looms|date=2011-10-02}}, ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'' Briefing Room, August 27, 2011.</ref> Becker's term, as a recess appointee, ended on December 31, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Media Journal coverage of the NLRB appointments|url=http://newmediajournal.us/indx.php/item/1450|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110702191440/http://newmediajournal.us/indx.php/item/1450|archive-date=2011-07-02|access-date=2011-06-27}}</ref> Hayes' term ended on December 16, 2012.<ref>Trottman, Melanie. [https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2012/12/17/labor-relations-board-loses-voice-of-dissent "Labor Board Loses Voice of Dissent"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610032505/https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2012/12/17/labor-relations-board-loses-voice-of-dissent/|date=2017-06-10}}, ''Wall Street Journal'', December 17, 2012; accessed 2013-01-27.</ref>

On January 4, 2012, Obama announced [[recess appointment]]s to three seats on the board: [[Sharon Block (government official)|Sharon Block]], Terence F. Flynn, and Richard Griffin.<ref>{{cite web|author=The White House, Office of the Press Secretary|date=January 4, 2012|title=President Obama Announces Recess Appointments to Key Administration Posts|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2012/01/04/president-obama-announces-recess-appointments-key-administration-posts|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216163521/https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2012/01/04/president-obama-announces-recess-appointments-key-administration-posts|archive-date=February 16, 2017|via=[[NARA|National Archives]]|work=[[whitehouse.gov]]|access-date=January 4, 2012}}</ref> The appointments were criticized by Republicans, including the House Speaker [[John Boehner]], as unconstitutional and "a brazen attempt to undercut the role of the Senate to advise and consent the executive branch on appointments."<ref>{{cite news|author=Helene Cooper|author2=Jennifer Steinhauer|date=January 4, 2012|title=Bucking Senate, Obama Appoints Consumer Chief|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/05/us/politics/richard-cordray-named-consumer-chief-in-recess-appointment.html?pagewanted=all|url-status=live|access-date=January 17, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120114200409/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/05/us/politics/richard-cordray-named-consumer-chief-in-recess-appointment.html?pagewanted=all|archive-date=January 14, 2012}}</ref> Although made as recess appointments, critics questioned their legality, arguing that Congress had not officially been in recess as pro forma sessions had been held.<ref>{{cite web|author=Charlie Savage|date=January 4, 2012|title=Obama tempts fight over recess appointments|url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/01/04/obama-tempts-fight-over-recess-appointments|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119005924/http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/01/04/obama-tempts-fight-over-recess-appointments/|archive-date=January 19, 2012|access-date=January 17, 2012|work=The Caucus|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref> Former U.S. attorney general [[Edwin Meese]] stated that in his opinion, since the appointments were made when the Senate was "demonstrably not in recess", they represented "a constitutional abuse of a high order."<ref>{{cite news|author=Edwin Meese|author2=Todd Gaziano|date=January 5, 2012|title=Obama's recess appointments are unconstitutional|newspaper=The Washington Post|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/obamas-recess-appointments-are-unconstitutional/2012/01/05/gIQAnWRfdP_story.html|url-status=live|access-date=January 17, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120003940/http://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/obamas-recess-appointments-are-unconstitutional/2012/01/05/gIQAnWRfdP_story.html|archive-date=January 20, 2012}}</ref> On January 12, 2012, the U.S. Justice Department released a memo stating that appointments made during pro forma sessions are supported by the Constitution and precedent.<ref>{{cite news|author=Seth Stern|date=January 12, 2012|title=Obama Has Recess Appointment Power, Justice Department Says|work=San Francisco Chronicle|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/g/a/2012/01/12/bloomberg_articlesLXP7PE6K50XW.DTL|access-date=January 17, 2012}}</ref>

On January 25, 2013, in ''Noel Canning v. NLRB'', a panel of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit|D.C. Circuit]] ruled that President Obama's recess appointments were invalid as they were not made during an intersession recess of the Senate, and the President moved to fill them during the same recess.<ref>Greenhouse, Steven. [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/26/us/labor-relations-board-rulings-could-be-undone.html "More Than 300 Labor Board Decisions Could Be Nullified"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171105214223/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/26/us/labor-relations-board-rulings-could-be-undone.html|date=2017-11-05}}, ''New York Times'', January 25, 2013; accessed 2013-01-26.</ref> On May 16, 2013, in ''National Labor Relations Board v. New Vista Nursing and Rehabilitation'', the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit|U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit]] became the second federal appellate court to rule that the recess appointments to the NLRB were unconstitutional. In a split decision, it also found that the March 27, 2010 recess appointment of Craig Becker was unconstitutional.<ref>Allenson, Sheryl C. and Milam-Perez, Lisa. [http://www.employmentlawdaily.com/index.php/2013/05/16/former-board-member-craig-becker-invalidly-recess-appointed/#sthash.ScW6uRak.dpuf "Former Board member Craig Becker invalidly recess-appointed; clause refers to 'intrasession break'"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203025412/http://www.employmentlawdaily.com/index.php/2013/05/16/former-board-member-craig-becker-invalidly-recess-appointed/#sthash.ScW6uRak.dpuf|date=2014-02-03}}, ''Employment Law Daily'', May 16, 2013; accessed February 1, 2014.</ref>

On July 14, 2013, Senate Majority Leader [[Harry Reid]] threatened to exercise the "[[nuclear option]]" and allow a simple majority (rather than a [[supermajority]]) of the Senate to end a [[filibuster]]. This threat to end the filibuster's privileged position in the Senate was intended to end Republican filibustering of NLRB nominees.<ref>Weisman, Jonathan and Parker, Ashley. [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/16/us/politics/democrats-seeing-precedent-press-on-to-curb-filibuster.html "Senate's Leader Sets Showdown Over Changes to Filibuster"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221101535/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/16/us/politics/democrats-seeing-precedent-press-on-to-curb-filibuster.html|date=2016-12-21}}, ''New York Times'', July 15, 2013; accessed 2013-07-16.</ref> On July 16, 2013, President Obama and Senate Republicans reached an agreement to end the impasse over NLRB appointees. Obama withdrew the pending nominations of Block and Griffin, and submit two new nominees: Nancy Schiffer, associate general counsel at the AFL-CIO, and Kent Hirozawa, chief counsel to NLRB Chairman Mark Gaston Pearce. Republicans agreed not to oppose a fourth nominee, to be submitted in 2014.<ref>[http://www.politico.com/story/2013/07/white-house-consults-with-afl-cio-head-on-nlrb-picks-94280.html Everett, Burgess and Bresnahan, John. "Obama Selects NLRB Replacement Picks"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201206215838/https://www.politico.com/story/2013/07/white-house-consults-with-afl-cio-head-on-nlrb-picks-094280|date=2020-12-06}}, ''Politico'', July 16, 2013; accessed July 16, 2013.</ref>

On July 30, 2013, the Senate confirmed all five of Obama's nominees for the NLRB: Kent Hirozawa, Harry I. Johnson III, [[Philip A. Miscimarra]], Mark Gaston Pearce and Nancy Schiffer. Johnson and Miscimarra represented the Republican nominees for the board.<ref>Cox, Ramsey.[http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/senate/314503-senate-votes-to-confirm-all-five-nlrb-members#ixzz2aemFMR3p "Senate Confirms All Five NLRB Members"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130801170434/http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/senate/314503-senate-votes-to-confirm-all-five-nlrb-members#ixzz2aemFMR3p|date=2013-08-01}}, ''The Hill'', July 30, 2013; accessed 2013-07-31.</ref> Pearce was confirmed for a second five-year term.<ref>[http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20130731/NEWS04/130739947/chicago-attorney-tapped-for-national-labor-relations-board "Chicago Attorney Tapped for National Labor Relations Board"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130804063848/http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20130731/NEWS04/130739947/chicago-attorney-tapped-for-national-labor-relations-board|date=2013-08-04}}, ''Chicago Business Journal'', July 31, 2013; accessed July 31, 2013.</ref>

On June 26, 2014, in ''[[National Labor Relations Board v. Noel Canning]],'' the U.S. Supreme Court unanimously ruled that President Obama's recess appointments to the NLRB in 2013 were unconstitutional, affirming the D.C. Circuit's decision in ''Noel Canning v. NLRB''.<ref>Liptak, Adam. [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/25/us/justices-agree-to-hear-case-on-presidents-recess-appointments.html "Justices to Hear Case on Obama's Recess Appointments"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170522003101/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/25/us/justices-agree-to-hear-case-on-presidents-recess-appointments.html|date=2017-05-22}}, ''New York Times'', June 24, 2013; accessed July 16, 2013.</ref><ref>Williams, Victor. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/victor-williams/the-supreme-court-should-_2_b_4586974.html "The Supreme Court Should Stay Out of the Noel Canning Recess Fight"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203195926/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/victor-williams/the-supreme-court-should-_2_b_4586974.html|date=2014-02-03}}, ''Huffington Post'', January 14, 2014; accessed February 1, 2014.</ref>

Nancy Schiffer's term ended on December 15, 2014. She was succeeded by Lauren McFerran on December 16, 2014. Harry I. Johnson III's term ended on August 27, 2015.<ref>[https://www.nlrb.gov/who-we-are/board/board-members-1935 NLRB official website] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304192558/https://www.nlrb.gov/who-we-are/board/board-members-1935|date=2016-03-04}}, nlrb.gov; accessed February 4, 2016.</ref>

==Structure==
{{more citations needed section|date=February 2018}}
[[File:1099 14th Street – National Labor Relations Board - sign.JPG|thumb|right|Plaque on the exterior of [[1099 14th Street]] NW in Washington, D.C., the NLRB headquarters as of 2013]]
[[File:NLRB picketing 2007.jpg|thumb|right|Union members picketing NLRB rulings outside the agency's [[Washington, D.C.]], headquarters in November 2007]]
In 1947, the [[Taft–Hartley Act]] created a formal administrative distinction between the Board and the General Counsel of the NLRB. In broad terms, the General Counsel is responsible for investigating and prosecuting [[unfair labor practice]] claims and for the general supervision of the NLRB field offices.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nlrb.gov/who-we-are/general-counsel|title=The General Counsel - NLRB|website=www.nlrb.gov|access-date=2017-04-21|archive-date=2017-04-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427024547/https://www.nlrb.gov/who-we-are/general-counsel|url-status=live}}</ref> The General Counsel is appointed by the President to a four-year term and independent from the Board; it has limited independence to argue for a change in the law in presenting cases to the Board. The General Counsel oversees four divisions: the Division of Operations Management, the Division of Administration, the Division of Advice, and the Division of Enforcement Litigation.

The Board, on the other hand, is the adjudicative body that decides the unfair labor practice cases brought to it. Once the Board has decided the issue, it is the General Counsel's responsibility to uphold the Board's decision, even if it is contrary to the position it advocated when presenting the case to the Board. The Board is also responsible for the administration of the Act's provisions governing the holding of elections and resolution of jurisdictional disputes. It is a reactive and not a proactive power. The NLRB rarely promulgates administrative rules.<ref>''Chamber of Comm. v. NLRB'', 721 F.3d 152 (4th Cir. 2011).</ref>

The Board has more than thirty regional offices. The regional offices conduct elections, investigate unfair labor practice charges, and make the initial determination on those charges (whether to dismiss, settle, or issue complaints). The Board has jurisdiction to hold elections and prosecute violations of the Act in [[Puerto Rico]] and [[American Samoa]].

===Jurisdiction===
The Board's [[jurisdiction]] is limited to [[private sector]] employees and the [[United States Postal Service]]; other than Postal Service employees, it has no authority over labor relations disputes involving governmental, [[railroad]] and [[airline]] employees covered by the [[Adamson Railway Labor Act]], or agricultural employees. On the other hand, in those parts of the private sector its jurisdictional standards are low enough to reach almost all employers whose business has any appreciable impact on [[interstate commerce]].

===Processing of charges===
Charges are filed by parties against unions or employers with the appropriate regional office. The regional office will investigate the complaint. If a violation is believed to exist, the region will take the case before an [[Administrative Law Judge]] who will conduct a hearing. The decision of the Administrative Law Judge may be reviewed by the five member Board. Board decisions are reviewable by [[United States Courts of Appeals]]. The Board's decisions are not self-executing: it must seek court enforcement in order to force a recalcitrant party to comply with its orders.<ref>''[https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=14047118090169598295 Mitchellace, Inc. v. NLRB]'', 90 F.3d 1150, 1159 (6th Cir. 1996).</ref> (For greater detail on this process see the entry for [[unfair labor practice]].)

==General Counsel==
[[Lafe Solomon]] was named Acting General Counsel on June{{nbsp}}21, 2010. His nomination was sent to the Senate on January{{nbsp}}5, 2011. Solomon's authority came into question on August{{nbsp}}13, 2013, when Judge [[Benjamin Settle]] for the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Washington]] denied a petition for [[Temporary restraining order#Injunctions in US labor law context|injunctive relief]], ruling that Solomon had not been properly appointed under the [[Federal Vacancies Reform Act of 1998]] (FVRA).<ref>{{citation |last=Trottman |first=Melanie |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2013/08/22/ruling-on-top-lawyer-adds-to-nlrb-questions |title=Ruling on Top Lawyer Adds to NLRB Questions |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=August 22, 2013 |access-date=August 22, 2013 |archive-date=August 22, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130822154346/http://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2013/08/22/ruling-on-top-lawyer-adds-to-nlrb-questions/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Although other [[United States district court|district courts]] had enforced Solomon's requests, Settle's decision called into question all of Solomon's activity since June{{nbsp}}21, 2010, focusing on subsections (a)(1) and (2) of the FVRA; some pundits claimed that Solomon's appointment was allowed under subsection (a)(3).<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.laborrelationstoday.com/2013/08/articles/presidential-appointments/another-setback-for-the-nlrb-federal-district-court-invalidates-the-acting-general-counsels-appointment |title=Another Setback for the NLRB: Federal District Court Invalidates the Acting General Counsel's Appointment |work=Labor Relations Today |date=August 22, 2013 |access-date=August 22, 2013 |archive-date=September 21, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921181056/http://www.laborrelationstoday.com/2013/08/articles/presidential-appointments/another-setback-for-the-nlrb-federal-district-court-invalidates-the-acting-general-counsels-appointment/ |url-status=live }}</ref> President Obama withdrew Solomon's nomination.<ref name=vail>{{citation |url=http://inthesetimes.com/working/entry/15380/senate_approves_new_members_for_national_labor_board |last=Vail |first=Bruce |title=National Labor Board Shutdown Averted as Senate Approves New Members |work=In These Times |date=July 31, 2013 |access-date=July 31, 2013 |archive-date=August 4, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130804215907/http://inthesetimes.com/working/entry/15380/senate_approves_new_members_for_national_labor_board/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

On July{{nbsp}}31, 2013, President Obama nominated former NLRB nominee Richard Griffin as General Counsel, calling Griffin "a kind of prosecutor at the board" who would fill "one of the most critical roles at the agency."<ref name="huffingtonpost_2013">{{cite web | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/17/richard-griffin-nlrb_n_3611585.html | title=Richard Griffin, Former NLRB Nominee, To Be Offered General Counsel Slot After Filibuster Deal | publisher=Huffington Post | date=July 18, 2013 | access-date=April 4, 2016 | first1=Dave | last1=Jamieson | first2=Ryan | last2=Grim | archive-date=April 17, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417080504/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/17/richard-griffin-nlrb_n_3611585.html | url-status=live }}</ref> The Senate approved Griffin's nomination on October{{nbsp}}29, 2013, by a vote of 55 to 44.<ref>{{cite news|last=Devaney|first=Tim|title=Rejected NLRB pick wins vote to serve as board counsel|work=The Washington Times|date=October 29, 2013|access-date=April 26, 2016|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/oct/29/obama-nlrb-counsel-pick-wins-key-vote/?page=all|archive-date=April 27, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427070448/http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/oct/29/obama-nlrb-counsel-pick-wins-key-vote/?page=all|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[Peter B. Robb]] was nominated by President [[Donald J. Trump]] in September{{nbsp}}2017 and was confirmed by the [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] on November{{nbsp}}8, 2017. He was sworn in as General Counsel of the National Labor Relations Board on November 17, 2017, for a four-year term. Immediately following [[Inauguration of Joe Biden|President Joe Biden's inauguration]] on January{{nbsp}}20, 2021, the White House sent a letter to Robb requesting his resignation. Just hours later, Robb refused, replying that he "respectfully decline[s] to resign" because the "removal of an incumbent General Counsel{{nbsp}}... is unprecedented" and "would set an unfortunate precedent for the labor relations of this country."<ref name="robb-letter-jan-21">{{cite web |last1=Robb |first1=Peter B. |title=[Letter to Cathy Russell] |url=https://aboutblaw.com/VaB |publisher=NLRB Office of the General Council |access-date=21 January 2021 |date=January 20, 2021}}</ref> He was fired that evening.<ref name="bl-ke-robb-jan-20-2021">{{cite news |last1=Kullgren |first1=Ian |last2=Eidelson |first2=Josh |title=NLRB General Counsel Robb Rebuffs Biden's Request to Resign |url=https://news.bloomberglaw.com/daily-labor-report/biden-moves-to-oust-top-labor-board-attorney-robb |access-date=21 January 2021 |work=Bloomberg Law |date=January 20, 2021}}</ref> In response, Representative [[Virginia Foxx]] (R–NC) said that the "outrageous ultimatum{{nbsp}}... is unacceptable and flouts the [[National Labor Relations Act]], while Representative [[Andy Levin]] (D–MI) called Robb a "toxic figure in the NLRB" who "worked to undermine its mission."<ref name="bl-ke-robb-jan-20-2021"/> Supporters of the firing argued that it was legal, citing the recent Supreme Court decision in ''[[Seila Law LLC v. Consumer Financial Protection Bureau]]'' (2020).<ref name="bl-ke-robb-jan-20-2021"/> The general counsel had never been fired previously.<ref name="Law360GCFired">{{cite news|title=Biden Fires NLRB GC Robb After He Declined To Resign|work=[[Law360]]|date=January 20, 2021|access-date=January 20, 2021|url=https://www.law360.com/articles/1347003}}</ref>

On January 25, 2021, President Biden appointed Peter Sung Ohr, a veteran employee of the NLRB, to serve as Acting General Counsel.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Biden Names Acting Top NLRB Lawyer After a Pair of Firings (1)|url=https://news.bloomberglaw.com/daily-labor-report/biden-taps-new-nlrb-top-lawyer-after-back-to-back-firings|access-date=2021-01-26|website=news.bloomberglaw.com|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=2021-01-25|title=After Unprecedented Firings of General Counsel and Deputy General Counsel, President Biden Names Peter Sung Ohr Acting General Counsel of the NLRB|url=https://www.laborrelationsupdate.com/nlrb/after-unprecedented-firings-of-general-counsel-and-deputy-general-counsel-president-biden-names-peter-sung-ohr-acting-general-counsel-of-the-nlrb/|access-date=2021-01-26|website=Labor Relations Update|language=en-US}}</ref> On February 17, 2021, Biden nominated [[Jennifer Abruzzo]], a former Acting General Counsel of the NLRB, to serve as the new General Counsel.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2021-02-17|title=President Biden Announces Key Nomination on Jobs Team|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2021/02/17/president-biden-announces-key-nomination-on-jobs-team/|access-date=2021-02-17|website=The White House|language=en-US}}</ref> Her nomination was confirmed by the Senate on July 21, 2021, in a 51–50 vote, with Vice President [[Kamala Harris]] [[List of tie-breaking votes cast by the vice president of the United States|breaking the tie]] in her favor.<ref>{{cite web |title=U.S. Senate Roll Call Vote 273 |url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=117&session=1&vote=00273 |access-date=23 July 2021}}</ref> Her four-year team in office began on July 22, 2021.

==Board members==

===Current board members===
