=== Recent appointments ===

====Donald Trump’s appointments====
On January 25, 2017, President [[Donald Trump]] appointed Philip Miscimarra the acting Chairman of the NLRB.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wiessner|first=Daniel|title=Trump taps Republican EEOC, NLRB members as acting chairs|work=Reuters|date=January 25, 2017|access-date=January 26, 2017|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/trump-appointments-idUSL1N1FF20G|archive-date=January 26, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126072439/http://www.reuters.com/article/trump-appointments-idUSL1N1FF20G|url-status=live}}</ref> Miscimarra's term expired on December 16, 2017. [[Marvin Kaplan (lawyer)|Marvin Kaplan]] succeeded him as NLRB Chairman on December 21, 2017.<ref name=nlrb_chair_confirm_vote>{{cite web|author=United States Senate|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=115&session=1&vote=00184|title=Confirmation Marvin Kaplan, of Kansas, to be a Member of the National Labor Relations Board|date=September 25, 2017|access-date=December 7, 2018|archive-date=January 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190114155359/https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=115&session=1&vote=00184|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=trump_named_kaplan_chairman>{{cite web|author=National Labor Relations Board|url=https://www.nlrb.gov/who-we-are/board/marvin-e-kaplan|title=Marvin E. Kaplan|access-date=December 7, 2018|archive-date=December 9, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209165223/https://www.nlrb.gov/who-we-are/board/marvin-e-kaplan|url-status=live}}</ref> Kaplan was replaced as chairman in April 2018 by [[John F. Ring]].<ref name=whitehouse>{{cite news|title=President Donald J. Trump Announces Intent to Nominate Personnel to Key Administration Posts|url=https://trumpwhitehouse.archives.gov/presidential-actions/president-donald-j-trump-announces-intent-nominate-personnel-key-administration-posts-12/|access-date=January 16, 2018|date=January 12, 2018|archive-date=January 20, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210120202604/https://trumpwhitehouse.archives.gov/presidential-actions/president-donald-j-trump-announces-intent-nominate-personnel-key-administration-posts-12/|via=[[NARA|National Archives]]|work=[[whitehouse.gov]]|url-status=live}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>

President Trump announced on March 2, 2020, that he would renominate Republican Marvin Kaplan and Democrat Lauren McGarity McFerran to seats on the board.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2020/mar/2/marvin-kaplan-lauren-mcferran-nominated-nlrb/|title=Trump nominates two to National Labor Relations Board|website=www.washingtontimes.com|access-date=29 July 2020|archive-date=4 August 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200804065143/https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2020/mar/2/marvin-kaplan-lauren-mcferran-nominated-nlrb/|url-status=live}}</ref> On July 29, 2020, Kaplan was confirmed by the Senate by a vote of 52–46 to a second term of five years expiring August 27, 2025, and McFerran was confirmed by the Senate by a vote of 53–42 to a second term of five years expiring December 16, 2024.

====Joe Biden's appointments====
On January 20, 2021, President [[Joe Biden]] appointed current Democratic member Lauren McFerran as chair of the NLRB.<ref name="Law360GCFired" />

Biden subsequently nominated [[Gwynne Wilcox]] to fill the then vacant Carmody seat on the board and David Prouty to replace [[William Emanuel]] as holder of the Smith seat when the latter's term expires in August 2021. Both nominees have strong ties to organized labor and have represented unions. They received [[Senate confirmation]] on July 28, 2021.<ref>{{Cite news|title=U.S. Senate approves union lawyers to NLRB, giving Democrats control|url=https://www.reuters.com/legal/legalindustry/senate-approves-union-lawyer-wilcox-nlrb-seat-2021-07-28/|access-date=2021-07-31|website=Reuters|date=29 July 2021|language=en|last1=Wiessner|first1=Daniel|last2=Shepardson|first2=David|last3=Wiessner|first3=Daniel}}</ref>

